1. Data preparation and exploration

This project is about exploring the death rate caused by unsanitary factors based on socioeconomic status (measured by GDP per capita) and population size. Therefore, I want to create a dataset that includes only the year, death rate, GDP per capita, and population for use in classification and clustering.

In the population(pop_data) and GDP per capita(pcap_data) data sets, years are treated as variable names, where each observation represents the population or GDP per capita of a country from 1960 to 2023.

1.3 Create the Year variable

The Year variable only exists in the death_data, while years exist as column names in the other data sets. What we want to do is to match the Country and Year variables from the data sets in order to explore the relationships among different variables. Therefore, we need to convert these two data sets into long format to get a new variable called Year. And we only explore the data after 1990 as the death_data data set does not records before that year.

In the death_data, some column names are not valid due to spaces, so we need to modify them. In pcap_data and pop_data, R added an X at the beginning of the variable names that start with numbers to make them valid. We need to remove the X during preprocessing.

# Convert the variable names in death_data to ensure they are valid R variable names
names(death_data) <- make.names(names(death_data), unique = TRUE)

# Convert pop_data and pcap_data into long format to create a new variable called "Year"
pop_data_long <- pop_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("X"), names_to = "Year", values_to = "population") %>%
  mutate(Year = as.numeric(gsub("^X", "", Year))) %>%
  filter(Year >= 1990)

pcap_data_long <- pcap_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("X"), names_to = "Year", values_to = "gdp.pcap") %>%
  mutate(Year = as.numeric(gsub("^X", "", Year))) %>%
  filter(Year >= 1990)

# View the converted data set

1.4 Clean the missing values

There are many missing values in the population and gdp.pcap variables after 1990, which could be due to some countries being established after 1990 or lack of records for certain years. We will first deal about the missing values in pcap_data_long and pop_data_long.

# Remove the observations where all the gdp.cap or population data is NA[1]
pcap_data_long <- pcap_data_long %>%
  group_by(Country.Name) %>%
  filter(!all(is.na(gdp.pcap))) %>%
  ungroup()

pop_data_long <- pop_data_long %>%
  group_by(Country.Name) %>%
  filter(!all(is.na(population))) %>%
  ungroup()

# View the data sets. As we can see, there are no NA values in the population variable, but there are still some NAs in gdp.pcap column. And we can reckon that the economic circumstances would not change significantly in several years for a certain country, so we need to do some data transformation.

# Perform linear interpolation for missing GDP per capita values, followed by forward and backward filling of remaining NAs
pcap_data_long <- pcap_data_long %>%
  group_by(Country.Name) %>%
  mutate(gdp.pcap = na.approx(gdp.pcap, Year, na.rm = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(gdp.pcap = na.locf(gdp.pcap, na.rm = FALSE)) %>%  # fill forward
  mutate(gdp.pcap = na.locf(gdp.pcap, fromLast = TRUE, na.rm = FALSE)) %>%  # fill backward
  ungroup()

1.6 Add the death.rate variable

Add a new variable named death.rate to death_data. The variables related to insanitation include Unsafe.water.source, No.access.to.handwashing.facility, and Unsafe.sanitation. We can define the death rate due to insanitation as the sum of these three columns divided by the population of that country in the corresponding year.

# Update the data set
death_data <- death_data %>%
  mutate(death.rate = (Unsafe.water.source + No.access.to.handwashing.facility + Unsafe.sanitation) / population)

# View the updated data set
head(death_data)

We can conclude that the overall death rate has been decreasing after 1990; the relationship between GDP per capita and the death rate is negatively correlated. we can take China as an example, the higher the GDP per capita, the lower the death rate tends to be.

# Scatter plot matrix of selected variables with variables on the diagonal for all countries

2. Classification

We use null model, decision tree, and logistic regression models to predict whether the death rates are high or low. Then compare the performance of the three classification models.

Overall both models have excellent performance compared with the null model. The logistic regression model shows higher AUC values than the decision tree model for both the training and test sets, which indicates that the logistic regression model has better overall discrimination ability compared to the decision tree model. But the decision tree model outperforms slightly than the losgitic regression one in terms of accuracy. And the Kappa values between both are close which indicates that they have similar consistency.

2.1 Split the training and test set

# Choose death rate category as the response variable. Use the lower quartile as a threshold to define death rates above this value as "high" and below as "low"
threshold <- quantile(data$death.rate, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
data <- data %>%
  mutate(death_category = ifelse(death.rate < threshold, "low", "high"))

# Convert death_category to the factor type
data$death_category <- as.factor(data$death_category)

# Set the random seed for reproducibility
set.seed(4009)

# Split the data set: 80% for training, 20% for testing
train_index <- createDataPartition(data$death_category, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- data[train_index, ]
test_data <- data[-train_index, ]

# View training and test data sets
head(train_data)
head(test_data)

2.2 Calculate feature information gain.

As we can see, the feature Year has an information gain of 0 so it can be ignored.

# Calculate information gain for features
info_gain <- information.gain(death_category ~ ., data = train_data)

2.4 The decision Tree Model

Choose gdp.pcap and population as the feature variables. The tree model illustrates that the lower gdp per capita leads to a higher death rate due to insanitation, which matches the perception.

The confusion matrices show that the decision tree model performs significantly better than the null model as the accuracy is higher than the null model. And the test set accuracy being close to the training accuracy suggests that the model generalizes well and is not overfitting.

The ROC for the Null model indicates a equivalent performance to random guessing as the AUC is 0.5. The ROC curves for training set and Test set are similar and close to the left-top corner, showing that it generalises discrimination well.

# Define model_type function, while the type is rpart
model_type.rpart <- function(x, ...) {
  return("classification")
}

# Define predict_model function
predict_model.rpart <- function(model, newdata, type, ...) {
  predictions <- predict(model, newdata, type = "prob")
  data.frame(low = predictions[, "low"], high = predictions[, "high"])
}

# Register to the global environment[3]
assign("model_type.rpart", model_type.rpart, envir = .GlobalEnv)
assign("predict_model.rpart", predict_model.rpart, envir = .GlobalEnv)

# Select the feature variables
features <- c("gdp.pcap", "population")

# Create an explainer for the decision tree model
explainer_tree <- lime(train_data[features], model = tree_model, bin_continuous = TRUE, n_bins = 10)


# Select the random test data samples to explain
set.seed(4009)
cases <- sample(1:nrow(test_data), 4)
example <- test_data[cases, features]

# Explain the decision tree model
explanation_tree <- lime::explain(example, explainer_tree, n_labels = 1, n_features = 4)


# Visualise the explanation of the decision tree model
plot_features(explanation_tree)

2.6 Logistic regression model

Choose gdp.pcap and population as the feature variables. At first the model performed poorly, as the auc value was lower than 0.2 and the accuracy in the confusion matrices was not satisfied, which means that it worked much worse than random guessing. So I decided to predict the death rate in reverse, meaning that I make the prediction probabilities higher than 0.25 as low, and vice versa. Then it works well.

Both the coefficients gdp.pcap and population have rather small Pr(>|z|) values which means that both of them significantly affect the model. And the deviance is smaller than the null model, indicating that the model has reduced the deiance.

The training and test set accuracies are 84.74% and 84.65% respectively. This indicates that the logistic regression model performs well in accuracy and consistency.

The ROC for the Null model indicates a equivalent performance to random guessing. The ROC curves for training set and Test set are similar and the area is higher than the null model, showing good classification ability.

3. Clustering

What we are exploring is the clustering of the numerical features(population and gdp per capita), so it is not appropriate to use Hamming distance, which is better at handling categorical variables. I chose the default Euclidean distance used in the K-means algorithm as the distance measure since it represents the straight-line distance between two points.

It can be seen from the plots that when k is equal to 9, the CH index is maximized, indicating the best clustering performance; when k is equal to 2, the ASW is the closest to 1, showing good separation and compactness of the samples; when k is equal to 3, it is the second best for the CH index and ASW.

By plotting scatter plots for clustering results when k equals 2, 3, and 9, we can conclude that when the number of clusters is 3, both indices perform well, providing a reasonable partition of the data while preventing overfitting, making 3 the optimal number of clusters.

3.1 preparations for clustering

# Select the feature variables for clustering
cluster_data <- data %>% select(gdp.pcap, population) %>% na.omit()

# Set the random seed to ensure reproducibility
set.seed(4009)

3.2 Determine the best number of clusters by the Calinski-Harabasz Index (CH Index) and the Average Silhouette Width (ASW)

Determine the optimal number of clusters (k) by means of the kmeansruns() function, using CH Index and ASW as evaluation metrics. The best value based on the Calinski Harabasz Index is 2, while the one based on the average silhouette width is 9.

# Set the random seed for reproducibility
set.seed(4009)

# Evaluate the number of clusters based on CH Index
kmClustering.ch <- kmeansruns(cluster_data, krange = 2:10, criterion = "ch")

# Evaluate the number of clusters based on ASW
kmClustering.asw <- kmeansruns(cluster_data, krange = 2:10, criterion = "asw")

# Check the optimal number of clusters based on the above two algorithms. 
kmClustering.ch$bestk
## [1] 9
kmClustering.asw$bestk
## [1] 2
# Create a dataframe for plotting
kmCritframe <- data.frame(k = 1:10, ch = kmClustering.ch$crit, asw = kmClustering.asw$crit)

# Plot the CH Index and ASW
fig1 <- ggplot(kmCritframe, aes(x = k, y = ch)) +
  geom_point() + geom_line(colour = "red") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10, labels = 2:10) +
  labs(y = "CH Index", x = "Number of Clusters") +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

fig2 <- ggplot(kmCritframe, aes(x = k, y = asw)) +
  geom_point() + geom_line(colour = "blue") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2:10, labels = 2:10) +
  labs(y = "ASW", x = "Number of Clusters") +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

# Display the two plots side by side
grid.arrange(fig1, fig2, nrow = 1)

3.3 Assume the number of clusters is 2

The data points are divided into two main categories, with the left cluster containing the majority of points concentrated in countries with smaller population sizes, while the right cluster mainly contains data in regions with larger populations. This indicates a significant distinction between countries with low population and those with high population, but there is greater dispersion within the left one, showing a large variance in GDP per capita.

# Apply K-Means clustering algorithm with 2 clusters
k2 <- 2
kmeans_result_2 <- kmeans(cluster_data, centers = k2, nstart = 20)

# Add the clustering results to the original data set
cluster_data_2 <- cluster_data %>% mutate(cluster = factor(kmeans_result_2$cluster))

# Plot the clustering results as a scatter plot
ggplot(cluster_data_2, aes(x = population, y = gdp.pcap, color = cluster)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(title = "K-Means Clustering Results (k=2)",
       x = "Population",
       y = "GDP per Capita") +
  theme_minimal()

3.4 Assume the number of clusters is 3

After dividing the data points into three categories, it is possible to further distinguish a group of countries with moderate population sizes, which differ from countries with lower and higher populations. This division allows the model to better display disparities between countries without leading to overfitting.

# Apply K-Means clustering algorithm with 3 clusters
k3 <- 3
kmeans_result_3 <- kmeans(cluster_data, centers = k3, nstart = 20)

# Add the clustering results to the original data set
cluster_data_3 <- cluster_data %>% mutate(cluster = factor(kmeans_result_3$cluster))

# Plot the clustering results as a scatter plot

  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(title = "K-Means Clustering Results (k=3)",
       x = "Population",
       y = "GDP per Capita") +
  theme_minimal()

3.5 Assume the number of clusters is 9

When the number of clusters is increased to 9, the data points are divided into more smaller categories, making it look rather confusing, especially for countries with lower population. Some clusters contain only a few data points, leading to overfitting of the small clusters and making it difficult to obtain meaningful information.

# Apply K-Means clustering algorithm with 9 clusters
k9 <- 9
kmeans_result_9 <- kmeans(cluster_data, centers = k9, nstart = 20)

# Add the clustering results to the original data set

  geom_point(size = 2) +

  theme_minimal()
